  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Signs Your Liverpool Shower Needs Replacing or Repairing</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Most shower problems can be resolved without a full replacement. We diagnose before recommending any work.</p>

      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Temperature fluctuates when taps are run elsewhere</strong><p>If the shower goes scalding hot or freezing cold when someone turns on a tap in another room, the thermostatic valve cartridge is worn. Valve cartridge replacement from £100 usually resolves this without replacing the whole unit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Poor water pressure from the shower head</strong><p>Limescale build-up in the shower head is the most common cause. A new shower head from £30 often resolves this. If pressure is poor across all outlets, the issue is the water supply or the pump rather than the shower itself.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Electric shower trips the circuit breaker</strong><p>An electric shower that trips the RCD usually has a failed heating element or a water ingress issue. The shower unit needs replacing. Elements cannot be repaired. We carry common electric shower units and can often replace on the same visit.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Shower valve leaking from the body or cartridge</strong><p>A leak from the shower valve body or cartridge can usually be resolved with a cartridge replacement or a new O-ring seal. We diagnose the source of the leak before recommending whether repair or replacement is the right call.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Shower tray cracked or leaking</strong><p>A cracked shower tray must be replaced. It cannot be repaired reliably. A tray that is leaking underneath can cause significant damage to the floor structure below, particularly in Liverpool's terraced properties with timber joists. We replace shower trays from £200 labour.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Shower over 10 years old and causing problems</strong><p>Electric showers typically last 5 to 10 years. A shower unit over 10 years old that is developing faults is usually more economical to replace than to repair. Parts availability for older electric showers decreases significantly after the 8 to 10 year mark.</p></div></div>
      </div>

